                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d15">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European Advisory Commission/60:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-24T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >January 24, 1944—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:06 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>632. Comea 17. The British have heard from their Embassy at Washington that a new
                    scheme is under advisement there for the treatment of the French civil affairs
                    question, and that this scheme would make unnecessary the clearance of the
                    existing “basic scheme” by the Advisory Commission (see my 544, January 20, 9
                    p.m., Comea 16<note n="42" xml:id="d15fn42">Not printed. This telegram stated
                        that the British wished to bring the document entitled “Civil Affairs in
                        France” before the next meeting of the European Advisory Commission; the
                        Ambassador requested further instructions on the subject (740.00119 European
                        Advisory Commission/56).</note>).</p>
                <p>They have therefore dropped their intention of bringing the existing paper before
                    the Commission at the next meeting, and are awaiting further clarification of
                    the matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Winant</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
